In [2477]:
# convert NeVaDa and Nevada? to Nevada in STATE column
train['STATE'] = train['STATE'].str.replace('NeVaDa', 'Nevada')
train['STATE'] = train['STATE'].str.replace('Nevada?', 'Nevada')
# drop row with STAR TREK in STATE column
train = train[train['STATE'] != 'Star Trek']
# drop row 'TT' in STATE column
train = train[train['STATE'] != 'TT']
# drop all rows in STATE which are not 'Nevada'
train = train[train['STATE'] == 'Nevada']

# ordinal encoding for columns: 'CURRENT_GRADE','FIRST_VIOLATION','SECOND_VIOLATION','THIRD_VIOLATION'

train['CURRENT_GRADE'] = enc.fit_transform(np.array(train['CURRENT_GRADE']).reshape(-1,1))
train['FIRST_VIOLATION'] = enc.fit_transform(np.array(train['FIRST_VIOLATION']).reshape(-1,1))
train['SECOND_VIOLATION'] = enc.fit_transform(np.array(train['SECOND_VIOLATION']).reshape(-1,1))
train['THIRD_VIOLATION'] = enc.fit_transform(np.array(train['THIRD_VIOLATION']).reshape(-1,1))

# get accuracy, recall, precision, f1 score
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred,zero_division=1))

from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
#implement all 
mnb = MultinomialNB()
bnb = BernoulliNB()
gnb = GaussianNB()
# Train the model using the training sets
mnb.fit(X_train, y_train)
bnb.fit(X_train, y_train)
gnb.fit(X_train, y_train)
# predict the response for test dataset for each model
y_pred_mnb = mnb.predict(X_test)
y_pred_bnb = bnb.predict(X_test)
y_pred_gnb = gnb.predict(X_test)
# get accuracy, recall, precision, f1 score
print('Accuracy of MultinomialNB classifier on test set: {:.2f}'.format(mnb.score(X_test, y_test)))
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_mnb))
print('Accuracy of BernoulliNB classifier on test set: {:.2f}'.format(bnb.score(X_test, y_test)))
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_bnb))
print('Accuracy of GaussianNB classifier on test set: {:.2f}'.format(gnb.score(X_test, y_test)))
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_gnb))

# output as csv file

The training data was initially cleaned by dropping the null values instead of imputing them because missing data makes up less than 1% of the overall dataset. The columns were converted to the appropriate data types and then cleaned for outliers or mistyped labels. Any additional inconsistencies in each column were either dropped or converted to the appropriate label. Categorical columns were converted to the Object datatype with ordinal ones being labelled as Category. Numerical Columns which represent nominal categories were also casted the Category data type with the true numerical values converted to either int or float based on the precision of data. Outliers in numerical columns were removed using the 3 sigma rule for identifying outlier values. Once the data has been cleaned and prepared, I performed various univariate and multivariate analysis on various numerical as well as categorical columns to understand the relationships between the variables, the distributions of various quantities, and identify the best features to use for the modelling process. Feature Selection techniques such as RFE (Recursive Feature Elimination) and Chi Squared Test to eliminate features that are independent of the target column. I then built a baseline model using Logistic Regression and used 7 feature columns to predict the target while achieving an accuracy score of 0.85. I also built other classification models such as Random Forest, Naive Bayes, Decision Tree, Gradient Boost Classifer, and KNN to observe that the accuracy rate ranges from 0.8-0.85 with the features that were picked. In classification the accuracy rate alone cannot determine how effective a certain model is and other metrics like precision, recall, f1 score in the form of a classification report must be considered before deciding upon the most optimal solution. Looking at the f1 score values of the various models I have constructed, Gaussian Naive Bayes appeared to have the most reasonable f1 score and a decent accuracy rate of 0.82. This model was picked over others despite it having a slightly lower accuracy rate due to the much higher f1 scores on all classes. This model was run on various samples of the train set using K folds to ensure consistency and the final model was used to make predictions on the test set. Among the various factors which may affect the performance of classification models, quality of the train data is a key criteria to ensuring the highest accuracy and f1 scores. The mediocre performance on the datasets could potentially be attributed to the lack of equal representation of both classes in the target column. In this case the values of class 0 significantly outnumber those that are from class 1 which could be the reason for the subpar f1 score. Some additional columns that could be added to this dataset include cuisine (cat),district (cat), comments(cat), food temperatures(num), sewage grade(cat), water quality(cat), food delivery date, age of food establishment. These columns could be used along with other columns like number of demerits and current grade to not only better understand the state of a restaurant but also predict its future performance.
